[normal]5.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Non-dependants are people who live in a benefit claimant’s household who are not dependant children, for instance adult children, other relatives and friends. 
[normal]It is a long-established principle 
[normal]of the benefit system 
[normal]that 
[normal]they 
[normal]should be expected to contribu
[normal]te towards the 
[normal]claimant’s 
[normal]housing costs. 
[normal]5.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the June 2010 Budget, the Chancellor announced a three-year staged increase in the rates o
[normal]f non-dependant 
[normal]deductions in housing b
[normal]enefit 
[normal]from April 2011. By April 2013, these increases brought the deduction rates
[normal] to the level they would have been had they been increased each year since 2001 to broadly reflect growth in rents. 
[normal]5.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The h
[normal]ousing 
[normal]b
[normal]enefit non-dependant deduction scheme is based on the age and circumstances of the non-dependant, and deductions are based on standard income-bands. The gross income of the non-dependant determines into which income band the non-dependant falls, and theref
[normal]ore the deduction that should be applied. There are a range of exemptions whereby a deduction does not apply. 
[normal]5.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department estimates
[normal] that around 350,000 non-dependants are living in households where deductions are made. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he Government believes there has to be a limit to the amount of benefit 
[normal]entitlement for 
[normal]people who are not in work. 
[normal]6.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Phased implementation 
[normal]of a cap on benefits 
[normal]started on 
[normal]15 April 2013
[normal] in Croydon, Bromley, 
[normal]Enfield
[normal] and Haringey. National rollout in other lo
[normal]cal authorities 
[normal]began in July and August
[normal], with the expectation that all appropriate households will be capped by the end of September 2013. 
[normal]6.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Applying the cap through housing benefit is an interim measure
[normal]. 
[normal]In the longer term the 
[normal]Department will administer t
[normal]he 
[normal]cap as part of the Universal Credit system.
[normal]6.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Latest figures show around 40,000 households are likely to be affected.
[normal]6.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The most vulnerable, including war widows, those in the support group for Employment Support Allowance, and those with severe disabilitie
[normal]s are exempt, as are households claiming Working Tax Credit.
[normal] 
[normal]Those in supported exempt accommodation will have their housing costs disregarded from the cap calculation. 
[normal]6.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]here is a 39 week grace period for those who have been in work for 50 of the previous
[normal] 52 weeks immediately preceding their last day of work.
