[normal]8.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universal Credit contains a significa
[normal]nt change of approach to the treatment of a 
[normal]contribution
[normal] to their housing costs by non-dependants.  Instead of the current complex scale of deductions that rise with the non-dependant’s income there is a single
[normal] 
[normal]flat rate of housing cost contribution which 
[normal]will apply, irrespective of income, to non-dependants aged 21 and over, where the person is either in work or there is an expectation that they should be working
[normal] or 
[normal]can return to work.   A contribution will not be expected if the person is a carer, is resp
[normal]onsible for a young child, or is in receipt of 
[normal]certain 
[normal]disability benefit
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universal 
[normal]Credit will help claimants prepare for work
[normal]. The Department has designed 
[normal]the payment arrangements to reflect those that apply to 
[normal]working people
[normal]. 
[normal]Supporting people to manage their finances including paying their rent will ease the transition into paid work.  
[normal]9.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are advantages in paying the housing 
[normal]costs 
[normal]element of Universal Credit direct 
[normal]to 
[normal]claimants
